-## General Syntax-Failure Guardrails
-
-For any retry after a Python `SyntaxError` or `py_compile` failure:
-
-- Prefer one Python file plus one test file at most.
-- Ask the worker for the smallest syntactically valid repair that can pass `py_compile` before adding fixture breadth.
-- Avoid long generated helper functions.
-- Avoid nested f-strings, inline regex construction, complex comprehensions, and multiline string literals in generated code.
-- Keep rejection reasons and classification names as module-level string constants.
-- Keep dataclass field annotations on field lines, not inside conditionals or expressions.
-- Use simple explicit conditionals over clever one-liners.
-- Run py_compile before full PP&D validation and treat any compile failure as a syntax-preflight failure, not as a normal unit-test failure.
-
-For any retry after TypeScript `TS1005`, `TS1109`, or `TS1128`:
-
-- Prefer one TypeScript file at most.
-- Avoid broad type contract rewrites.
-- Keep interfaces and object literals small.
-- Run the TypeScript command before broader tests.
-
